<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - PISTONS
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>PISTONS</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="4">
            <title>Inspection</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect the pistons for scuffed or scored skirts and cracked or worn lands.
                    Replace the pistons as required.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check top and intermediate compression ring groove widths for wear as follows:</para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>THESE ENGINES USE FULL KEYSTONE COMPRESSION RINGS (FIRST AND SECOND GROOVE) AND A
                            RECTANGULAR OIL CONTROL RING. THE PISTON RING GROOVE CONFIGURATION CORRESPONDS TO THE SHAPE
                            OF THE PISTON RING (FIGURE 6.11). THE KEYSTONE COMPRESSION RING GROOVES ARE MEASURED OVER
                            GAUGE PINS TO DETERMINE WEAR. THE RECTANGULAR OIL CONTROL RING GROOVE DOES
                            <emph type="underscr">NOT</emph>
                            USE GAUGE PINS, BUT SIDE CLEARANCE TO DETERMINE PISTON RING GROOVE WEAR.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the 0.1150 in. (2.921 mm) gauge pins from the piston groove wear gauge pin
                        set (
                        <emph type="bold">ZTSE3020</emph>), into the groove to be measured. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050611">6.11</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>GAUGE PINS MUST BE PARALLEL</para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Measure the piston diameter over gauge pins using an outside micrometer,
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050612">6.12</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">measurement over the gauge pins is
                        <emph type="bold">NOT</emph>
                        within specifications, excessive piston groove wear exists and the piston must be replaced with
                        new. Refer to "
                        <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS".</emph>
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050611" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2406" filename="../figeg2/EG2406.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.11.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Piston</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Top Ring</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Intermediate Ring</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. Oil Control Ring</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050612" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2414" filename="../figeg2/EG2414.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.12.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Micrometer</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Piston Ring Gauge</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Piston</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the rectangular oil control ring groove for side clearance as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Using a new ring, place the outer edge of the ring in the oil control ring groove.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Roll the ring, in its respective groove, entirely around the piston. Make sure the
                        ring is "free" in the groove.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">With a feeler gauge check the side clearance of each oil control ring in its
                        respective groove,
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050613">6.13</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Excessive side clearance indicates ring groove wear and requires piston
                        replacement.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check piston to cylinder sleeve running clearance, as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Measure and record the piston skirt diameter. With the piston at room temperature,
                        place an outside micrometer 1.080 in. (27.43 mm) below the bottom land of the oil control ring,
                        90 degrees from the pin bore. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050614">6.14</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Measure cylinder sleeve inside diameter, refer to
                        <emph type="bold">"CYLINDER SLEEVE INSPECTION"</emph>
                        later in this section for the procedure. Record the reading.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Subtract the piston skirt diameter from the cylinder sleeve I.D. The resulting
                        dimension is the piston to cylinder sleeve running clearance.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If running clearance is not within
                        <emph type="bold">"SPECIFICATIONS"</emph>, replace the piston.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050613" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2415" filename="../figeg2/EG2415.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.13.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Piston</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Oil Control Ring</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Feeler Gauge</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050614" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2416" filename="../figeg2/EG2416.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.14.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Micrometer</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Piston</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
